## Port Rule

Never guess ports.

Before starting any HTTP or TCP service, obtain a named port:

```sh
PORT=$(${portbroker_command} get --name <service> 2>/dev/null || ${portbroker_command} alloc --name <service> --host ${default_host} --persistent)
```

Bind services to `${default_host}` unless the user explicitly requests a
different host.

Any new HTTP service should expose:

```text
GET /whoami
```

The response should include:

```json
{"service":"<service>","version":"<version>","pid":123,"startedAt":"<iso8601>","host":"${default_host}","port":1234}
```

If a port is needed in docs or commands, document the `PORT=$(...)` pattern
instead of hard-coding common ports such as 3000, 5000, 8000, or 8080.

When unsure, inspect current reservations and listeners:

```sh
${portbroker_command} list
ss -ltnp
```

## Prose Hygiene

Use `${prose_hygiene_command}` when asked to scrub prose, remove em dashes, or
